title: Cooling Fan mount for Rostock Max V3

description.text:
Hello All,

To combat my EZstruder's stepper motor heating and deforming the filament going into the bowden tube, I designed this Fan Mount for SeeMeCnc's Rostock Max V3. This mod has brought my Stepper Motor's temperature down about 18°C (see pics above). Since it also serves the entire top compartment of the Printer, it helps with the RAMBo and Pi boards I have in there. Note that the intake air is only as cool as the ambient air around your printer (the enclosure is next...).

The fan mount uses a standard 120 mm Computer case fan. I tricked mine out with a Thermaltake Ring fan. The mod mounts directly onto the existing injection-molded panel mounts with the same hardware for the melamine panels (melamine panel removed). Use 4mm hardware to mount the fan to the mount (the hex openings are 7.5 mm flat to flat). I also added a wire way for the fan wiring into the upper compartment of the printer (sexy-factor). Wired the 120 mm fan into the existing 40 mm fan connection on the RAMBo board. The only thing I might do in the future is get a dust filter for the fan intake. Enjoy...

title: Anet A8 Z Axis CHUNK Reinforcement Top Mount & Z Motor Mount

description.text:
Significantly increase the stiffness of the Z axis arrangement.
Ties the leadscrew together with the bearing rod at the top with a ball bearing.
Tight fitting bearing rod points prevent the rods from being able to move.
Threaded rod between the two top mounts removes the Anet A8 cross bar flex and acts as a corner brace with the uprights.
Z Motor housings now single piece, and include a screw down point on the outer edge for fastening to a base board.

Top mounts are prepared with a 6.8mm diameter hole to allow tapping to M8 for the threaded bar tie rod. 8mm clearance through to the other side.

1: After printing, insert the bearing (should be a simple press fit)
2: Use an M8 tap to tap the tie rod hole from the washer flat side
3: Fit Z bearing rods into top blocks until all the way in. Do this on a flat wooden surface and tap the rod in until it stops moving.
4: Replace the Z motor housings. Clean out the bearing rod hole before fitting as this is also a good fit on the bearing rod.
5: Fit the top mounts with the bearing rods and guide the lower end of the bearing rod into the Z motor mount, and the top of the leadscrew into the ball bearing.
6: Use the original top mount M3 screws to fix the top mounts down.
7: Use the Z motor housing screwdown points to screw the A8 to the baseboard.
8: Re-level your bed & X Axis
9: Hopefully enjoy a reduction in Z banding!

Sounds like a lot of work, but actually only a 30 minute job once the parts are printed.

Top mounts take 1 x 608ZZ bearing each
Join the two top mounts using M8 threaded rod & nuts

This controller was created to control the Robovent dust collection system that is used to control room (atmospheric) pressure for Field Debris Wind Tunnel testing at the John Deere Aero-Thermal Performance Lab. This controller will adjust the Robovent VFD frequency to maintain a pre-determined room pressure. This is needed because as the unit under test begins to plug during debris testing the pressure in the room will increase (from more negative to less negative), assuming a constant Robovent speed, because the wind tunnel cannot replace the air being evacuated from the room as fast as it previously was. As these changes are happening this controller will make the changes necessary on the Robovent to give us more precise and consistent test data.

Introduction To do this we decided to use a Raspberry Pi 3 B as our compute module to handle all of the thinking to be done. This is a standalone microcontroller that runs on a Linux based Operating System. It has 1GB of RAM and a 64-Bit quad core processor with a clock speed of 1.2 GHz. This is more powerful than we would ever need in the life of this project and for the price it was an easy decision. There are also 40 GPIO (General Purpose Input/Output) pins located on the PCB (Printed Circuit Board). These pins will be useful for interfacing with other devices, such as the Robovent and the analog pressure sensor. The digital pressure sensor is what we will use to supply the Raspberry Pi with the pressure data in the room. In short, the pressure sensor will send a 4-20 mA signal to the Raspberry Pi which will send a 0-10V signal to the Robovent accordingly.

Handle an Input

description.text:
This is a face plate/cover plate for my Chinese dual AK4490 DAC.
It is pretty thick (3mm), but my first try was just too wobbly.

The plate can be screwed to the cinch and optical ports and also has an extrusion to fix it to the two mounting holes on the PCB.
I didn't note down what screws I bought, but they're just cheap screws from the hardware store. Measurements: 8.14mm overall length, 5.5mm shaft length; head has 5.44mm diameter, shaft 2.86. So I suppose it's a M2x5.5.

The design had one small bug, which is fixed in rev1: Since I made the "PCB screw hole mounts" larger than required (to compensate for any measurement errors), I had to add a spacing for the resistor at the coax input - but I put it on the wrong side (and had to cut it away). This was fixed by shortening the mounts from 12mm to 9mm.

While at it, I uploaded the Autodesk Inventor 2018 source file.

The DAC is this one: https://www.aliexpress.com/wholesale?SearchText=double+ak4490eq+board (I got mine from "HiFi College Store).

Oh, nothing fancy, just an analog square wave synthesizer -- That's OKAY... 2!

This is like the original OKAY but sports two octave of keys and an 1/4" audio out jack.

  • Monophonic: Only one note at a time can be played. This is opposed to “polyphonic,” where multiple simultaneous notes can be played.
  • Analog: There are no computers, microcontrollers, sound samplers, or anything digital involved. The sound you hear is the sound of a speaker being abused by discrete electronic components like capacitors and resistors and logic chips.
  • Square-wave: When its output is viewed on an oscilloscope, its wave resembles a square. It’s a “hard” sounding wave type, great for bass lines, and commonly associated with chiptune music and old video games.

These are the 3D models for the OKAY 2 Synth DIY Kit. Read more about it here.

Differences from OKAY 1: more keys, keys and key bed PCBs mounted to internal cradle piece, no key plungers, audio out jack

Advice

  • The enclosure models are pretty big and are prone to warping. Minimize that risk by using a filament with low shrinkage like PLA and ensuring very good bed adhesion.

When using my turntable on high volumes, the bass was creating a feedback loop which was enough to cause the needle to jump. I was even able to start the feedback loop by hitting the carpet.

I tried a number of different ideas and suggestions, before finding a comment on a forum. Someone said that years ago in the clubs, they would use rubber bands on ashtrays to support the turntable.

This gave me the idea of creating something which I can attach rubber bands to for support.

After testing, I am no longer getting the feedback loop.

This project has two parts

  • The main support area with mounting points for the rubber bands
  • The leg extension. This just sits on top of the rubber bands. Depending on the feet on your player and weight, this may not be needed or you may need to make it longer

I found standard envelope rubber bands work when doubled over. Double them over, then stretch them only at the point you are putting it over the mounting points. This allows it to fit while still being springy in the middle.
You will need a minimum of two rubber bands crossing in the middle, but you can add more if your player is heavy.

description.text:
This is a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2474906. Big thanks to "disser" for giving me ideas!
The remixed part is the bracket that fits on the Leaf. I made it a bit beefier, changed angle, and added a hole that allows to rotate the phone dock without it falling out. So you can use it horizontally or vertically, and switch on the fly.
The dock can take a wireless charging pad:
https://www.amazon.ca/gp/product/B01L3OUC7W/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o09_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
It fits pretty much any phone I think...
With Android, I have tasker set so that when i put the phone on it, it starts Android Auto and turns the screen lock off. And it restores that when taking the phone off the dock (detect wireless charging and car usb connection).

You could easily use the bracket to hold something else in the car, just use the cookie cutter file I uploaded to cut another of your designs!

If you make one, please upload!

Printer:

Prusa i3 acrylic frame

Infill:

20-30%

There are 5 parts. Really, it is pretty self explanatory for the most part, but for the clamp, you will need a spring, and a nail...
-I used an extension spring 5/32" diameter (about 4mm), with a C-C distance of about 1-3/8" (35mm).
-There is 1 small hole in the clamp, and 1 in the main body. I used a steel nail that I cut short, and that fits exactly in the holes. Those 2 nails are the pins that retain the spring. So you 1st slide the spring in the clamp and put the nail in. Then you slide the clamp in the main body and put the 2nd nail in the main body, thru the loop in the spring. This one is a bit tricky sometimes, make sure your spring will reach the hole. Otherwise you can always drill another hole where you need it.
-Then you glue the knob on the back of the main body (there is a shallow pocket just for that).
-Glue the side stop in the side shallow pocket of the main body.
-I recommend adding a thin foam pad (found at craft stores) at the bottom of the hole, in the bracket. I used a 0.08" (2mm) thick foam pad. That way the dock won't turn on it's own, it really puts a friction between the knob and the bracket, which is desired.
-That's about it, the bracket goes on top of the dash above the air vent, and it clips real good in the air vent as you see on pictures. It never fell once yet and I have it there for months.

description.text:
This is a beefy heat bed wire harness for the Monoprice Select Mini 3D Printer.

This part is intended to be used as a apart of the common heat bed wire modification that is often required to prevent damage of the heat bed wires during Y axis movement.

The part has an integrated zip tie holder that can be used to secure the heat bed wires to the harness to prevent stress on the heat bed solder joints during movement

WARNING: Use caution with the zip tie as if it is too large, it may interfere with the lowest Z-Axis level. Place you zip tie on, tighten it, pull the bed completely forward, and lower the z axis completely. Make sure the zip tie head does not interfere with the gantry. If it does, use a smaller zip tie.

I used M3 screws and nuts to secure the wire harness to the bed.

title: Mazda 6 2014 Universal phone dock Wireless charger

description.text:
This is a remix of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2474906. Big thanks to "disser" for giving me ideas!
The remixed part is the bracket that fits on the Leaf. I used the idea to make a bracket for the Mazda 6 2014. The bracket is completely different, but the idea came from that.
The dock can be used horizontally or vertically, and switch on the fly.
The dock can take a wireless charging pad:
https://www.amazon.ca/gp/product/B01L3OUC7W/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o09_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
It fits pretty much any phone I think...
With Android, I have tasker set so that when i put the phone on it, it starts Android Auto and turns the screen lock off. And it restores that when taking the phone off the dock (detect wireless charging and car usb connection).

You could easily use the bracket to hold something else in the car, just use the cookie cutter file I uploaded to cut another of your designs!

If you make one, please upload!

Printer:

Prusa i3 acrylic frame

Infill:

20-30%

There are 5 parts. Really, it is pretty self explanatory for the most part, but for the clamp, you will need a spring, and a nail...
-I used an extension spring 5/32" diameter (about 4mm), with a C-C distance of about 1-3/8" (35mm).
-There is 1 small hole in the clamp, and 1 in the main body. I used a steel nail that I cut short, and that fits exactly in the holes. Those 2 nails are the pins that retain the spring. So you 1st slide the spring in the clamp and put the nail in. Then you slide the clamp in the main body and put the 2nd nail in the main body, thru the loop in the spring. This one is a bit tricky sometimes, make sure your spring will reach the hole. Otherwise you can always drill another hole where you need it.
-Then you glue the knob on the back of the main body (there is a shallow pocket just for that).
-Glue the side stop in the side shallow pocket of the main body.
-I recommend adding a thin foam pad (found at craft stores) at the bottom of the hole, in the bracket. I used a 0.08" (2mm) thick foam pad. That way the dock won't turn on it's own, it really puts a friction between the knob and the bracket, which is desired.
-That's about it, the bracket goes on top of the dash and it clips inside of the cd player slot. It clips in pretty solid, it never fell once yet and I have it there for months.

description.text:
A remix of pbeyl's "Yet Another Micro SD Card Storage Case" which was itself a remix of bgill's "Micro SD Card Holder" to turn the center four MicroSD card slots on both sides into nano USB device holder slots... because I don't have 16 MicroSD cards I carry around, but I do have several MicroSD cards plus some nano wifi, bluetooth, etc USB adapters that I normally just keep loose in an Altoids tin.

Modifications to the bottom were simply cutting out the solid material between two of the existing MicroSD slots, then extending the now thicker slots by 0.5mm toward both the center line and outer edge to make them slightly wider as well.

The top was extended by 5mm to give a bit more headroom for USB devices of varying heights, as my Edimax wifi adapter is only about 2.5mm taller than a MicroSD card, but a Fitbit USB adapter is as much as 6.2mm taller. That said, even with the extra height inside allowing the MicroSD cards more slack space to slide up and down when it's closed, it still seems low enough to keep them from actually coming out of their slots even when shaken with intent to dislodge them.

Note: The top does screw on pretty snugly, and I followed pbeyl's comment on his model to soften it up a bit in some hot water, and worked it back and forth until it was a bit easier to screw on and off.

description.text:
UPDATES:
1/24/2018 - I have added the option of using thumbwheels to level the bed. The change to the materials used is minimal (the new setup uses 4-40x1" machine screws for bed adjustments instead of the 6-32x1" used previously) and there are slight edits to all of the parts. Also, I still have the original no-thumbscrews bed holders uploaded here in case you prefer the original style. Make sure you sand the edges of the thumbwheels lightly to know down any extra protrusions as the clearance is semi-tight. Also, A dab of glue on the top of the screws to stop them from spinning when turning the thumbwheel inst a bad idea.

PROJECT SUMMARY:
This is a modification to expand the MonoPrice Select Mini's print bed depth to 230mm on the cheap. I am able to utilize a printable area of 130mm x 220mm with just these modifications. The price once built was approximately $60 for me. This is nearly the same price as the unheated version of the "4th dimension modifications" "Maximus" kit but my build includes a heated bed. Note that you will need to upgrade the Select Mini's power supply to utilize the heater but I hope to be making a basic guide for that as well soon.

SOME NOTES:

  • No special tools (except a 3D printer) are needed for this project. I used a hacksaw to cut the aluminum, scissors, a drill with 1/8" and 5/32" drill bits, and a measuring device.
  • Most of the non-3D printer specific parts (8mm rod, belt, and the bed itself) were purchased from my local Ace Hardware.
  • I used a lot of Imperial sized (6-32) bolts instead of Metric (M3 or M4) bolts. Im in the US, so they are WAY cheaper locally. Seriously, like 1/3 to 1/2 the price. Sorry, I'd rather use metric too... M4 will PROBABLY work fine and allow use of the nut inserts.

LINKS:
Print Bed:
Note: This link is probably sold out (sorry, maybe my fault) but the bed is appears to be an aftermarket replacement for the FlashForge Pro, so searching for "flashforge pro bed" on eBay seems to turn up desirable results.
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01AAYY70Y/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
Belt:
Note: this is WAY too much belt. You only need ~30cm and could save money by buying a smaller quantity.
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00F2IQNX8/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
Rods:
https://www.ebay.com/itm/300-350-400mm-8mm-Chromed-Rod-Parts-DIY-CNC-Linear-Rail-Shaft-for-3D-Printer/122850462999?hash=item1c9a754d17:m:m3bE2vd9IhcoeTMEq0XmC7Q
Everything else was locally purchased at Ace Hardware.

A REALLY REALLY BRIEF BUILD GUIDE:
Looking at your printer as it comes apart is crucial. This "guide" is very broad and skips a lot of stuff that you should be able to figure out on your own.

  • Printing
    I printed everything with 100% infill and 0.1mm layers with PLA. Time will tell if the PLA holds up tot he heat from the print bed but I am confident. I am able to fit it all in 3 print files on the stock Select Mini. It took a long time but it is very rigid and looks good IMO.

  • Cutting Aluminum:
    Cut aluminum to 150mm for the front and rear and approximately 2-5mm shorter than your rods for the left and right sides. Its ok for the aluminum to be a few mm short but not a few mm long.

  • Drilling:
    Assemble and square the frame off of the printer. Ensure that the 8mm rods are against the aluminum and are the same spacing as on the printer. Use a 1/8" drill bit to drill through the holes in the 3D printer parts. Expand the holes shown in the pictures in the aluminum only. The expanded holes are to allow for some adjustability in the system.

  • Assembly:
    When the frame is initially assembled on the printer, do not tighten the 2 screws in the front and rear that were drilled oversized. Push the frame to the farthest back point of travel and tighten the front screw and vise versa. This prevent binding.

  • Installing the bed
    When installing the bed, I placed the connector for the electronics toward the outside of the printer. It will bind if placed on the inside.

  • Installing the belt:
    The belt loops through this frame differently than the stock printer. However, it still goes through the stepper motors the same way and the layout in the frame should be obvious. The ribs in the belt will sit in the ribs on the inside edge of the frame.

description.text:
BIBO Touch 2 Dual Extruder 3D Printer Flexion Extruder Bracket:
Installing the Flexion Extruder isn’t too hard but does take a bit of extra work. All of the materials I used to make this work are from the 3D printer except for the electrical tape:

  • The 3D printed bracket
  • 2 screws from the bottom electrical plate
  • 2 white plastic spacers found on the screws above
  • Electrical tape
    Make sure to follow the instructions and USE THE ELECTRICAL TAPE WHERE NEEDED. I am not responsible for any damage. Everything should work great if you follow the instructions.
  1. The Flexion Extruder sits higher than the top of the extruder motor so you need to print the bracket to act as a spacer between the motors and the top mount. Print the bracket with the holes facing down so no supports are needed. I used a 60% infill, 3 walls, and a 0.1200 layer height.
  2. Unscrew the 4 screws located on the top mount which act as spacers currently before installing the Flexion Extruder.
  3. Follow the instructions supplied by Flexion for installing the extruder with one change. As the hotend comes with the shorter PTFE tube inserted, the nozzle will sit too high and not be able to reach the print bed. It will also be higher than the screws holding the extruder assembly together which won't work. Remove this PTFE tube and use the longer one that is also provided in the kit (meant to be used at the top). Flexion instructs you to push the hotend against the cooling block for a proper fit. Try this and make note of where the end of the PTFE tube meets the extruder gear. Now push the hotend with the longer PTFE tube so that the PTFE tube is in the proper position (tight against the gears) and tighten the screw on the cooling block. You can order a short length of PTFE tube, cut it in the 'V' shape and use it at the top if needed. I have not had any trouble with it so far.
  4. The BIBO 3D Printer hotends are not compatible with the Flexion cooling block so you will want to purchase a dual Flexion kit or buy a true mk10 hotend for the second extruder.
  5. Once you have finished with Flexion’s instructions, place the bracket in between the motors and top mount with the screw holes facing up and to the front of the extruder. Screw the front to screws directly into the new bracket. The original 2 screws that hold the top mount to the extruder assembly are not long enough. I took 2 of the 4 screws that hold the bottom plate under the 3D Printer and used them. Place 1 white spacer first for each screw (they are already on the 2 screws) and then thread the screws through the top mount and tighten them down.
  6. Finally, the bed will not lower enough for the new nozzle height. Remove one spring and the washer from each of the 3 leveling screws on the bed. Put electrical tape on the black bracket under the solder points of the wires for the heated bed so that they cannot come in contact with the black bracket.
  7. You are now done!

The parts listed here can be used to construct a simple spectrophotomer, which illuminates a sample in a cuvette with an LED and then measures the amount of light transmitted through the sample with a photoresistor (on the opposite side of the cuvette). The voltage across the photoresistor can be measured using an Arduino. In short, as the absorbance of the sample increases, the voltage across the photoresistor will decrease.

Several parts are listed here, including:
1) An enclosure that will hold an Arduino and the rest of the LED/photoresistor circuit.
2) A simple cuvette holder that grips the cuvette and holds the LED/photoresistor in place on either side of it.
3) A more advance cuvette holder with multiple pieces (LED holder, cuvette/photoresistor holder, and a cuvette removal tool), which fully conceals the cuvette from ambient light.

To better see what is going on below the nozzle i bought a view of LED strips.

As the exact bed "zero" level of each of you may differ i designed the .scad file with a parameter height.

The height is measured from the rig to the top edge of the led-strip (in my case 63mm).

Make it high enough that the LEDs can enlight the bed, but keep it low enough, that it does not collide with the z-mounting, while z-leveling.

title: Splint for heated bed plate (HBP) connector on older MakerGear M2s

description.text:
This part is an accessory for the MakerGear M2.  It is designed to clip around the heated bed wire connector, and it serves the dual purpose of keeping the heater connector from separating, and preventing the wire from kinking behind the connector.  Newer versions of the M2 (mine is from January 2013) use strong and flexible automotive cable on this connector, but the earlier versions can break the wire after enough flexing.  
m2_splint_v5.stl is an updated version that better follows the natural curve of the cable.  The fingers on the flexible part are longer and slightly curved to better hold the cable, and there is an additional notch on the side to accomodate the thermocouple wire.

One photograph shows the piece installed on the connector in the back of the M2 printer,  The other photograph shows what happened to the printer connector in the first place.  The wire kinked behind the connector, and after enough flexing, it broke, smoked, and melted the wire.  Re-soldering it was a 15 minute job, but it wasn't something I wanted to see happen again.  
I'm not sure when MakerGear switched to the automotive wire, but it's never a bad idea to have a cable guide.  
As far as installation, this piece just clips over the connector.  Refer to the photograph if needed.

title: Universal magnetic mount for Pi Zero with Cam

description.text:
I designed a mount for my Pi Zero Case (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2689387). Which allows me to mount and remove it dynamically to/from my 3D Printers. Im using an A8, but depending on the design of your heatbed it should work on other printers too.
I'll add some fotos/videos later this evening.

Example Video of a print:
https://youtu.be/qnWC-Y4VIfw

Materials needed:
6x 6x4mm Magnets
Double sided tape or another good glue
Flat piece of magnetic material.

Assembly

  1. Put the holder and the arm together
    The ball joint should pop in with some force. For me it was abit stiff due to cooling problems on top, which deformed the ball so I had to sand it abit.
    If you sand it too much and the friction is too low ( like I did ) just add some tape to the ball to gain more friction.
    Add six 6x4mm Magnets to the holes in the arm. Tape or glue them so they dont drop out afterwards.

  2. I used double sided tape to glue a small piece of iron below my heatbed, since the aluminium is not magnetic.

  3. I noticed that on fast movements of the Printers Y Axis there was some movement on the X Axis of the camera. To stabilize this you can use the clamp. Find a good spot for your cam than glue the clamp to the iron in that position. You still can pull off and attach the camera very quickly with it.

description.text:
UPDATE: An improved version 2 of this sword is now available, complete with scabbard. I recommend using that version over this one.

Every budding Witcher needs their trusty twin swords, and here we have the Mastercrafted Wolven Steel sword from the Witcher 3. (Silver available at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2767062)

Being scaled to the lore and the game files, the hilt is 12" long, and the blade a further 40.5". A pair of holes are present down the blade in order to house two 2mm x 1m long carbon fibre cores and keep everything together. These are designed to poke slightly out of the blade and into the hilt for truer centering. A second hole also runs down the length of the hilt and into the blade in order to contain a 1/8" x 3/8" steel core.

The grip is designed so that you can wrap a 3mm thick leather cord around them and have a true look to the game designs.

The runes read "One made of steel" / "for humans" as a callback to an in-game quote, as well as "Valentine Costumes" (my cosplay brand) - if you wish I am willing to customise this file with your own text or different runes (price dependant on changes) - please feel free to contact me if you're interested in this service.

Due to common transportation issues with large blades such as this, it is designed to come apart where the blade and hilt meet. If you attach the hilt to the aforementioned metal core, you can then drill a 5mm hole in the core at the point where a hole features in the top of the blade (Blade_7 file), and then use a 3.5mm binding screw to hold it all together.

Please feel free to use / modify this model as you wish, but credit is always appreciated.

Now get out there and kill some monsters

title: MK8 Extruder Mount with built in print cooling ring for Sintron Prusa i3

description.text:
I had a few issues with the original bracket supplied with the kit. While it worked, it relied on the plastic flexing to get the extruder in and out and I managed to break it. I managed to fix it and it work for a while, but it melted trying to print on a (very) hot day. Some very dodgy fixes made it possible to print an improved version with inbuilt print cooling ring.

This version has a number of improvents over the original:

  • Built in print cooling ring and fan
  • Make in two parts so that the plastic does not have to flex to install and remove the extruder (and possibly break).
  • Hopefully solid enough not to melt.
  • Can be mounted with screws from the back of the X carraige so the extruder does not have to be taken out of the bracket in order to remove the assembly from the machine.
  • The adapter for the fan is a separate piece, so you can design one to suit your fan without having to reprint the whole thing.

There is also a file attached with just the bracket and no cooling ring if you would prefer it that way.
Made with OpenSCAD

I designed this Anet A8 Y Axis Belt tensioner for GT2 Aluminum Pulleys. You will need ø 5mm metal plug which fits directly into the 5,2mm hole(still tight enough) and inside the Pulley. See example links below. You can buy the metal plug in your lokal hardware store. This is where I found mines. They are simple parts to keep furnitures etc. together.

I printed at 30% infill. Don't use less cause this parts need to be stable. You will have to print:
Screw 1x
Plate 1x
Tensioner 2x

description.text: This an HO scale join for train tracks and can be used to replace small pieces of ballast under the tracks. It is to scale. I find with the PECO track it needs to be printed at 101% otherwise it pushes the track apart.

Notes:

This must be printed with ABS as the fine clips to hold the track break if printed with PLA.
Project

Ultimate TEVO TARANTULA upgrade.

This thing is a result of months spent on upgrading my Tarantula. Wanted printer which is reliable and more rigid than stock one. Therefore all acrylic parts were removed and replaced with elements designed from scratch. I did reuse some brackets designed by thingirob. See description below.

X and Y axis

To get rid of all play introduced by stock wheels I decided to switch to mgn9 linear rail on x axis and mgn12 linear rail on y axis. X and Y axis parts include belt tensioners. There are two versions of y axis belt tensioners available. Use Y_YAxisBeltTensioner1.stl Y_YAxisBeltTensioner2.stl if you want it to be easier to use or Y_YAxisBeltTensionerShort.stl if you want to fit your Tarantula into IKEA STUVA cabinet (I use it as enclosure). To be able to mount linear rails make sure you have some t-nuts with m3 thread. Mgn9 rail should ordered in version H. Mgn12 rail should be one which fits your Y carriage.

Z axis

Z axis was upgraded with 8mm rods and LM8UU linear bearings. Stock stepper and lead screw was replaced with two stepper motors with integrated lead screw. I used 400mm version but 360mm lead screw should be enough.

Extruder and hotend

Extruder assembly was reworked as well. Now it is fully printable direct extruder working with genuine e3d v6 hotend and volcano upgrade. I used 8mm inductive proximity for bed leveling.

WARNING e3d hotend without volcano upgrade will be too short to reach the bed and will NOT be compatible with layer fan duct!

Electronics

To keep my wires in order I designed mks board case and some helping elements for wiring management (I use MKS Base v1.2 board). Noctua fan is used to keep board cool. It turned out that it is effective enough to skip mosfet upgrade. It is Noctua NF-A9x14 fan.

How to print it

Use ABS or PETG. If remember correctly I sued 0.3mm layer height, 3 perimeters and 35% infill. If you decide to use ABS it is recommended to use Skirt/Brim to prevent corners lifting.

Additional parts

To complete this build you will beed brackets designed by thingirob which could be found here:

description.text:
Before he ascended the throne of Crete, Minos struggled with his brothers for the right to rule. Minos prayed to Poseidon to send him a snow-white bull, as a sign of approval by the gods for his reign. He promised to sacrifice the bull as an offering, and as a symbol of subservience. A beautiful white bull rose from the sea, but when Minos saw it, he coveted it for himself. He assumed that Poseidon would not mind, so he kept it and sacrificed the best specimen from his herd instead. When Poseidon learned about the deceit, he made Pasipha, Minos' wife, fall madly in love with the bull. She had Daedalus, the famous architect, make a wooden cow for her. Pasipha climbed into the decoy and fooled the white bull. The offspring of their lovemaking was a monster called the Minotaur.
The creature had the head and tail of a bull on the body of a man. It caused such terror and destruction on Crete that Daedalus was summoned again, but this time by Minos himself. He ordered the architect to build a gigantic, intricate labyrinth from which escape would be impossible. The Minotaur was captured and locked in the labyrinth. Every year for nine years, seven youths and maidens came as tribute from Athens. These young people were also locked in the labyrinth for the Minotaur to feast upon.
When the Greek hero Theseus reached Athens, he learned of the Minotaur and the sacrifices, and wanted to end this. He volunteered to go to Crete as one of the victims. Upon his arrival in Crete, he met Ariadne, Minos's daughter, who fell in love with him. She promised she would provide the means to escape from the maze if he agreed to marry her. When Theseus did, she gave him a simple ball of thread, which he was to fasten close to the entrance of the maze. He made his way through the maze, while unwinding the thread, and he stumbled upon the sleeping Minotaur. He beat it to death and led the others back to the entrance by following the thread.
